Before you do radioactive iodine you have to do a two-week low iodine diet and if you're wondering "but where am I getting iodine from?" I can tell you, EVERYWHERE. Table salt, obviously. So all professed food. Dairy. Frozen peas. (Both in processing.) Anything from the ocean.

Clarification! It's iodine your thyroid loves, which can become radioactive in the event of an event. Potassium iodide fills up your thyroid with normal iodine so you can't absorb the bad kind. I swear I knew all this when I had to take therapeutic radioactive iodine!

Also you don't want to be taking them like a supplement "just in case." It's only in the event of ... an event. So you just keep the one dose or whatever around and if something far enough away that it doesn't kill you goes boom, then you take the dose.
Unless you live near a nuclear energy facility, buying up potassium iodide is kinda silly.

It doesn't do shit to protect any other part of your body. 
Thyroid cancer sucks but it's maybe the least of your problems if you're in a blast zone.
Basically the pills are for energy plant disasters not nuclear war.
